{"schema_version": "1.0", "timestamp": "2026-06-15T12:36:47.707996+00:00", "run_id": "20260615-223048-581121", "turn_id": "20260615-223124-586858", "event_id": "20260615-223048-581121-00019", "event": "assistant", "component": "integration", "phase": "output", "status": "completed", "source": "live", "message": "Assistant RAG response recorded", "duration_ms": null, "metrics": {}, "artifacts": [], "error": null, "payload": {"kind": "rag_message", "content": {"answer": "The retrieved papers explore various aspects of LLMs, including implicit biases, safety risks, hallucinations in code generation, multi-agent systems, and applications in personal health. They collectively highlight challenges in bias detection, safety, and reliability of LLMs across different domains.\n\n**Key findings:**\n\n- LLMs exhibit implicit biases that can perpetuate stereotypes, detectable via novel psychological-inspired methods like LLM Implicit Association Test (IAT) Bias and LLM Decision Bias (source: 2407.01270).\n\n- LLM-based agents are vulnerable to attacks, with Evil Geniuses (EG) demonstrating high success rates in generating harmful prompts (source: 2311.11855).\n\n- LLMs generate hallucinated code in complex scenarios, with a proposed RAG-based mitigation method showing effectiveness (source: 2409.20550).\n\n- Integrating Theory of Mind and internal beliefs in multi-agent systems improves collaborative decision-making, though performance depends on LLM capabilities (source: 2603.00142).\n\n- PH-LLM, a health-focused LLM, outperforms human experts in fitness-related tasks and demonstrates the value of multimodal data encoding (source: 2406.06474).\n\n**Research gaps:**\n\n- Limited understanding of how cognitive mechanisms like ToM and internal beliefs interact in multi-agent systems (source: 2603.00142).\n\n- Insufficient exploration of safety and robustness of LLM-based agents in real-world environments (source: 2311.11855).\n\n- Need for more comprehensive frameworks to detect 